</CodeI><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gpol"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gpir"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gpir"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Politics/International Relations</CodeD><CodeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="860380"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018571-20180322-025042"/></CodeI><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gpol"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">N/GEN N/PLT R/ASI R/FEO R/KN R/SK </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com NORTH KOREA SOUTH KOREA SOUTH KOREAN PRESIDENT TERM LIMITS SB126955385469309739639045841169502403160421 SYND CODES_REVIEWED Asia News </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OASN </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">South Korean President Proposes Extending Term Limits; Proposed changes aim to give presidents more time to implement North Korea policy</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>SEOULâ€”South Korea's leader proposed changing the constitution to allow presidents to serve up to eight years over two terms, instead of the current limit of one five-year term, a shift that advocates say would provide more stability in Seoul's <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-south-korean-presidents-discuss-north-korea-nuclear-talks-1521225128">policies toward North Korea</ELink>.</Para><Para>President Moon Jae-in's office on Thursday said officials were reviewing the proposal, which was among his campaign promises last year. Mr. Moon's predecessor, Park Geun-hye, had also promised to push through a plan to extend term limits, but legislation was never introduced.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The intended changes would require approval by two-thirds of South Korean lawmakers and a majority of the public in a referendum that could be held as early as June, coinciding with local elections.</Para><Para>Since 1987, South Korean leaders have been limited to a single five-year term, a safeguard that was implemented after decades of military dictatorship.</Para><Para>"Recent public surveys show the great majority of the public approve of a presidential system based on four-year terms, with the possibility of re-election," Mr. Moon's office said in a statement outlining the measures.</Para><Para>A two-term presidential system typically has earned the support of between 40% and 50% of respondents in recent polls, according to the National Assembly Research Service, a legislative think tank.</Para><Para>Proponents and critics of the move acknowledged that if implemented, the change would provide greater policy certainty, allowing more time for Seoul's leaders to execute their approaches on critical issues such as <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-u-s-north-korea-meeting-reflects-victory-for-moon-jae-in-1520572528">South Korea's relationship with the North</ELink>.</Para><Para>The possibility of re-election would incentivize presidents to more aggressively produce results on North Korea, said Choi Young-jin, professor of Korean politics at Chung-Ang University.</Para><Para>Others are skeptical that extending term limits would substantially affect relations between the two Koreas.</Para><Para>"I have reservations on whether this will be a major improvement, as the fundamental problem in talking to North Korea is Pyongyang's uniquely deceptive negotiating tactics," said Yoon Pyeong-joong, professor of political philosophy at Hanshin University in Seoul.</Para><Para>Mr. Moon, who was elected in May last year, wouldn't be subject to the changes, his office said. Under the proposal, presidents wouldn't be able to serve nonconsecutive second terms.</Para><Para>Mr. Moon also proposed other changes to the constitution, including requiring presidential pardons be reviewed by an independent committee. Another proposal would lower the voting age to 18 from 19, in line with the age that South Koreans can legally marry and work in government.</Para><Para>Write to Andrew Jeong at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:andrew.jeong@wsj.com">andrew.jeong@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>Related</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-south-korean-presidents-discuss-north-korea-nuclear-talks-1521225128?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=2">U.S. and South Korean Presidents Discuss North Korea Nuclear Talks</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-to-hold-first-known-meeting-with-south-korea-1520244394?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=14">Kim Jong Un Holds First Known Meeting With South Korea</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korean-president-hopes-olympics-will-prompt-u-s-dialogue-with-north-1518879152?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=31">South Korean President Hopes Olympics Will Prompt U.S. Dialogue With North</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Andrew Jeong